<div id="subtree-container" class="subtree-container"><div class="aea2d7dde423afa7ad9351a0886150a8-scss b51b00c1669ad99a1c607cd1e77c2824-scss" style="inset: 228px 269px 0px 0px; justify-content: flex-end;"><div class="afeebf1df237d4103108ba40799802d6-scss"><div class="c13443431e58facf06f9d12490b92a82-scss" style="width: 90vw; max-width: 8.5in;"><div class="_0df5ec6b9902d7d22ccfa3ebb4f35211-scss">Model-derived Takeoff - Ratios</div><div class="e5e059a27f4c194020f0d961a3cb5989-scss" dir="auto"><div class="fr-view"><p id="isPasted">This method involves estimating rebar weight by applying a reinforcement ratio (kg/m³ or lb/yd³) to the concrete volume of the modelled structure.&nbsp;</p>
<p>To enhance the precision of reinforcement estimation, it's critical to validate the structural model's join order, ensuring accurate element joins as mandated by he chosen rules of measurement for concrete structure quantification (see example illustrated in Figure 05).&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;<img src="https://private.lodplanner.com/projects/53934/plan-content/1710501153376_c9f99972-9aa2-4526-bc46-746b518ac27e.png?Expires=1768815902&amp;Signature=WlOeSGSUD33gd5AH~zUuw~Y5R4YuRpMvO3PpVlRvMJWtrUuM4wej2aQDZYfsrpQN661tF8Hhlf9ETkJI1MdlujwBHLOzbzIXUjtX2eMW-xzindL5jNqL4syug2MpDIKxVjxBs7PBqo~ZmrbIuHVB3gTMCHkUaTibr-PHDeAK0pezeq0WUv2zxoyfAAUmkjrDHhzv3EJj3YkXjMPtEjj0Cz9Bo-GqJH1C4lGiIafbn86kd2eAwBIckgFb1gQsX~F0bDtGGnLvz9x1IXbiB44QF8jJfAP-ysbQyiJFgmUpVRMpMT4-fBMlCBxUHIvxFWI-GfUXhychsXm7b8uZsyPHPQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAJRIVA6WNZT4BZJPQ" style="width: 660px;" class="fr-fic fr-dib"></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Figure 05 - Illustration of the schedule quantification of intersected volumes of concrete structural elements, in this case, a beam and a slab.&nbsp;</em></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>This step ensures that the concrete volume adheres to the chosen rules of measurement and serve as base for accurate estimation of rebar quantities for each category.</p>
<p>If rebar modelling is not required by the EIR, this method can be employed to all project phases.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div>